[Black "Pure Symmetrical: 5.Nf3 e5 with 7.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights which will be looked at later. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most popular and challenging move. It accounts for more than half of the games in the Pure Symmetrical. }
5... e5
{ We will go for the reversed Botvinnik setup. It is solid, yet ambitious. Black grabs space at the cost of weakening the d5-square. Decades of practice have shown that Black can get away with this. In fact, he can usually fight for d5 - after all, he has the same pieces to control it with that White does! }
6. O-O
{ Deviations from this move such as  6.d3  and  6.a3  are covered in the main course. }
6... d6 7. d3 Nge7 8. a3
{ This is the main move, but other tries here can be found in the full course. }
8... O-O 9. Rb1 a5 10. Ne1
{ This is a very common position where Black has done very well. White begins his knight tour, but after this Black will not have to bother with ...h6 because there is no Nf3-g5. }
10... Be6 { Black is all set to play ...d5. } 11. Nd5
{ Physically preventing ...d5.   11.Nc2  allowing ...d5 is considered in the next line. }
11... Rb8 { A very typical move to get familiar with. } 12. Nc2
{ The most common but probably not the best. } 12... b5 13. Nce3 f5
{ This makes a lot of sense, as Bg5 is not possible. Black is just better, with more space across the board. }
