1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3
{ This little prophylactic move is second in popularity, with almost as many games played as 6. g3. White takes a move to prevent ...Bb4 while maintaining maximum flexibility. While 6. g3 presents more of a memory challenge, 6.a3 makes it more difficult for Black to create active counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ There are other options, but with ...Bb4 off the table, I like this simple developing move. }
7. e4
{ This is the most popular move. White wants to play a Hedgehog, even though he has already spent a move on 6. a3.  I am not a big Hedgehog player, but I know that usually Black does not put a knight on c6 @@StartBracket@@...Nbd7 would be more typical@@EndBracket@@. Because of these two factors I believe Black should play rather directly, because ...Nc6 is a developing move while a3 was not! }
7... O-O
{ Now Black is hoping to play ...d5 when White does not have his Hedgehog, but Black does have his development lead. }
8. Nc2
{ Ok, here at least White is preventing the ...d5 break. The b3-square is weak though. This may not seem relevant, but watch... }
8... b6
{ This is Black's other plan if ...d5 does not work. But it won't be such a typical Hedgehog. }
9. f4 { This was played by some Magnus Carlsen guy. } 9... Bb7 10. Bd3 Rc8 11.
Qe2
{ This was Carlsen - Topalov, Nice 2009. Now Black should exploit his development lead with: }
11... d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 d4 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Ne4 Bh4+
{ White's position is kind of a mess. } 16. g3
{ 16.Kd1  Re8  Black has various threats. } 16... f5 17. O-O Re8
{ White would do well to survive for a few more moves. } *

