[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6.
Ndb5 { This is an important move. White takes aim at the d6- and c7-squares. }
6... d5 7. Bf4
{ This is more critical than greedy pawn grabbing with  7.cxd5  .  There's a little threat with Nc7+, so Black's reply is forced. }
7... e5 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6
{ We cannot trade queens ourselves because Nc7+ would still hang over our head. So we have to allow our king to be displaced. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's king is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the bishop pair and open lines for his rooks.   It's dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking the initiative. }
11. O-O-O+
{ This is very natural. White gets the rook to the d-file with tempo, secures his king, and protects the b2-pawn - all in one move. But there is a downside - the f2-pawn is a glaring weakness. }
11... Ke7
{ This modern move was likely rejected for a long time because of its clumsy appearance. However, the king is quite safe here, and ...g6 will soon take care of the f8-bishop. Black has done very here, and engines are already favoring Black. }
*

