[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3
{ This little prophylactic move is second in popularity, with almost as many games played as 6. g3. White takes a move to prevent ...Bb4 while maintaining maximum flexibility. While 6. g3 presents more of a memory challenge, 6.a3 makes it more difficult for Black to create active counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ There are other options, but with ...Bb4 off the table, I like this simple developing move. }
7. g3 { This looks a bit odd to me. } 7... Qb6
{ Now this works out rather well, as it does in the main lines with 6. g3 Qb6. }
8. Nb3
{ A typical move, but the knight is not very stable here and this causes tactical problems. }
8... Ne5 { Already White is in trouble! } 9. e4 Nfg4
{ Black is already winning. In the analogous position without a3 and ...Be7, White would play Qe2 here, but now the b3-knight would drop. }
10. c5 { Too late! } 10... Qxb3 { 0-1 Ma Qun - Raznikov Groningen 2014. After }
11. Qxb3 { the black knights run roughshod over White's position: } 11... Nf3+
12. Kd1 { 12.Ke2  Nd4+ } 12... Nxf2+ 13. Ke2 Nd4+ 14. Kxf2 Nxb3
{ It's not often you see a 2600+ player lose with White in ten moves! } *

