[Black "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Nb3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. }
7. Nb3 Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. Qe2
{ This is the main line. White protects the e4-pawn, and also covers the c4-pawn to prepare Bg2. }
9... d6
{ Bringing some protection to the dark squares. Black has to time ...Bxc3 carefully, because if the capture is done too early White will be able to play Ba3 and the bishop will slice through Black's position. Now White chooses between immediate aggression in the center or the prevention of doubled pawns. }
10. Bd2
{ White prevents doubled c-pawns and prepares to castle long. Play can become very sharp, but Black is doing quite well. }
10... O-O
{ It was a tough choice between this and  10...a5!?  but ultimately I favored the flexibility of immediate castling. }
11. O-O-O Bd7
{ The traditional move is   11...a5  when  12.f4  a4!  leads to tremendous complications. Black is ok here too, but it is a lot to remember. I think that the move 11... Bd7 is at least as strong. Black intends ...Rfc8, and ...a5 is always a possibility as well. }
12. f4
{ With ...Rfc8 coming to attack the c4-pawn, this is the only move to avoid a quick disaster. }
12... Ng6
{ I imagine that 11... Bd7 was ignored for a long time because   12...Nc6?  13.e5!  is good for White. Black's point is that now: }
13. e5 dxe5 14. fxe5 { can be met with } 14... Bc6
{ The rook has nowhere to go. } 15. Bg2 Bxg2 16. Qxg2 Nxe5
{ With an extra pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bg2 #1"]
[Black "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. }
7. Ndb5 Ne5 8. Bg2
{ This is an obvious move, if you discard the fact that the c4-pawn is hanging. }
8... a6 9. Qa4
{ This is the main line, but moves such as  9.Na4!?  and  9.Na3  are analysed as well in the full repertoire.  The queen pins the a6-pawn in order to maintain the b5-knight. White hopes to create tactical problems before he is pushed back. }
9... Rb8
{ The rook could be vulnerable here, but now the b5-knight is attacked again. }
10. Be3 Bc5
{ Do not fall for this little trick:   10...axb5?  11.Bxb6  bxa4  12.Bc7+- }
11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qa3
{ 12.Na3  O-O  Black has a great position with ...d6, ...Bd7, and ...b5 in mind. }
12... b6 13. Nd6+ Ke7 14. Qxc5 bxc5 15. Nxc8+ Rhxc8
{ Black has mobilized with great speed and has nice play in the endgame. I would not expect many White players to go for this. It's not the kind of position one would stumble into, and White has more enterprising ways to play. }
16. b3 d5 { This is not the only possibility, but it's the most aggressive. }
17. cxd5 c4
{ White has to be quite careful here or his queenside will fall apart. Black's knights are very active, while the g2-bishop can't help defend White's queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bg2 #1"]
[Black "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. }
7. Ndb5 Ne5 8. Bf4 Nfg4 { This defends the e5-knight and attacks the f2-pawn. }
9. Qa4
{ This wild looking move was first played by Aronian in a game against Leko. White simply allows ...Qxf2+. }
9... Qxf2+
{ Ok, this is very obvious, and yet I adorn it with  !? Generally, this immediate capture has been considered to be inaccurate, but I think it is a good move.  Leko took 80 minutes! on  9...g5  and this is still the main line. After  10.Bxe5  Leko played  10...Nxe5  , which is playable but leads to a slight edge for White. }
10. Kd2
{ This is necessary. Instead  10.Kd1  Kd8!  guards the c7-square and ...Ne3+ will come next. }
10... g5
{ This deflection idea is seen several times in the 7. Ndb5 line in the full repertoire. }
11. Nc7+ Kd8 { Two of White's pieces are hanging, so his reply is forced. } 12.
Bxe5 Qe3+ 13. Kc2 Qxe5 14. Nxa8 Ne3+ 15. Kb3 Bc5
{ Black seems to be doing rather well here. He has more pieces in play and dominates in the center. Of course the a8-knight is in some trouble too. Black would like to play ...Ke7, ...d5, ...Bd7, and then ...Rxa8. That's a lot of moves to make, but it's not clear what White can do! }
