[White "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bf4"]
[Black "Pure Symmetrical: 5.Nf3 e5 with 7.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights which will be looked at later. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most popular and challenging move. It accounts for more than half of the games in the Pure Symmetrical. }
5... e5
{ We will go for the reversed Botvinnik setup. It is solid, yet ambitious. Black grabs space at the cost of weakening the d5-square. Decades of practice have shown that Black can get away with this. In fact, he can usually fight for d5 - after all, he has the same pieces to control it with that White does! }
6. O-O
{ Deviations from this move such as  6.d3  and  6.a3  are covered in the main course. }
6... d6 7. a3
{ Another move order would be  7.d3  Nge7  8.a3   8.Ne1  Be6  is the 7.Ne1 line as covered in the first variation of this course.  8...a5  9.Ne1   9.Rb1  O-O  reaches the 7. d3 lines that were just examined.  9...Be6  10.Nc2 }
7... a5
{ I used to think that this was a concession, as White has not had to spend a tempo on Rb1 yet. Black has recently shown that his position is quite viable anyway.   Instead,  7...Nge7  8.b4  transposes to 6... Nge7 7. a3 d6 8. b4 - a pleasant line for White that we are avoiding. }
8. Ne1 Be6
{ The point of the 6... d6 move order.   Not  8...Nge7  9.Nc2  Be6  10.Ne3  with an edge for White. }
9. d3 { After  9.Nd5  Nge7  10.Nc2  O-O  11.d3  we reach 10. Nd5. } 9... Nge7
10. Nc2
{ White allows the ...d5 break counting on the fact that he has not bothered to spend a tempo on Rb1 to allow him to develop some initiative.   10.Nd5  is possible, but this the 'wrong knight' - White wants to play Nc2-e3-d5.  10...O-O  11.Nc2  Rb8!  12.b4  axb4  12...b5!?  13.axb4  cxb4  14.Ncxb4  Nxb4  15.Nxb4  d5= }
10... d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne3
{ This position is 'supposed to be' good for White. } 12... Nb6
{ This move has revitalized Black's whole concept. The thematic  12...Nde7  is three times more common, but White has better chances of an edge here. The addition of the moves a3 &...a5 benefits White, as the b6- and b5-squares are weakened.  13.Nc4  O-O  14.Bg5  f6  15.Be3  b6  16.Qa4  and f4. I think Black is actually ok here, but he will have to be more careful.  16...Qc7   If  16...Rc8  17.Qb5!  17.f4  Rab8  18.fxe5  Nxe5  when White chooses between  19.Nxe5  and  19.Bf4  . Black is holding, but  12...Nb6  is more challenging for White to meet. }
13. Bxc6+
{ This is White's main try, and probably the most challenging move. White gives up his proud bishop to wreck the black structure. Here the addition of a3+... a5 favors Black, as White's light squares, particularly b3, have been weakened. }
13... bxc6
{ Black's structure is wrecked, but White had to give up his king's best defender. Both sides should keep an eye on Black's breaks with ...c4 and ...e4, even as pawn sacrifices. The lines continue in the main course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bf4"]
[Black "Pure Symmetrical: 5.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights which will be looked at later. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e4
{ Trying to use our own weapons against us! Well, we know White can equalize and get an interesting game, but that's ok. }
5... Nf6
{ I am going to show a way of playing that I accidentally invented when playing a very strong former student of mine. }
6. Nge2 O-O { There are various move orders here, but this is most logical. }
7. d3
{ This looks best - remember we played ...d6 quickly in the same setup with Black. }
7... d6 8. O-O a6 9. h3 { Avoiding  9.Be3  Ng4  . } 9... Rb8 10. a4 Bd7
{ Or  10...Ne8  11.Be3  when Black has generally prevented  d4 with the 'wrong' knight:   11...Nd4   but there is also the interesting  11...b5!?  which is not even a pawn sacrifice:  12.axb5  axb5  13.Nxb5  Nc7=   or  13.cxb5  Nd4 }
11. Be3 e5
{ I made this up at the board, and it's pretty good! This move is also not considered in Marin's series on the English Opening for White. We now have a 'double Botvinnnik' of sorts, but Black's knight is on the f6-square. It could be considered to be misplaced, but I do not think matters are so simple.   In this structure, pushing the f-pawn is not always so great, as a subsequent exf5/...exf4 opens the diagonal for a blocked bishop. Decades of playing the Botvinnik setup has also taught me to be careful with the e7-knight, as it is not always so manoeuvrable. The f6-knight has potential pathways to improvement, most notably with ...Ne8-c7.   Lastly, in this pawn structure, the move Be3/Be6 can be premature, as Nd5/...Nd4 can be annoying because capturing with a knight would lose a piece. Here White's bishop is already on e3, while our bishop is on the d7-square. I know sometimes this means it's more passive, but here I'll say it's more flexible! }
12. f4 { It's good to see how to play after this. } 12... exf4 13. Nxf4
{ 13.Bxf4  Be6  14.Qd2  Now Bf4-g5 could be annoying.  14...Qc7!  This covers the d6-pawn and prepares ...Nd7-e5.  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.exd5  Na5!  Black has clear counterplay. }
13... Ne8
{ From here the knight will go to c7, when it may trade off a knight on d5, or come to e6 and d4. }
