[White "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bf4"]
[Black "Three Knights - 'Maroczy Fail'"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 { This is the most combative move. } 4. d4
{ White is going for a Maroczy Bind, but he is not in time to do so. So I called this line the Maroczy Fail. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7
{ The d4-knight is attacked, so there is no time for e2-e4. } 6. Nc2 Bxc3+
{ I have always loved this idea. The doubled c-pawns will give Black very clear counterplay. }
7. bxc3 Qa5
{ This is the main line. There are different move orders Black can use. It's not clear which is best. This is the most direct, but it can also wait. Black is not always in a hurry to take on c3 as it takes time and may give life to White's dark-squared bishop. Often the c4-pawn is the real target. }
8. Bd2 Nf6 9. f3 d6 10. e4 Be6
{ Black has many decent moves, but I played this myself against Smirin when he was #19 in the world. }
11. Nd4 { This is usually nothing to fear. } 11... Rc8 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qb3
Qc5 { 13...Qc7  and   13...O-O  are also possible. } 14. Qxb7 Rb8 15. Qa6 O-O
16. Qa4 Nxe4 { Surprise!   16...Rb2  is just as strong. } 17. fxe4 Qf2+ 18. Kd1
Rb2 19. Be1 { 19.Bh6  Qxf1+  mates. } 19... Qe3 { Black has a winning attack. }
*

