[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Four Knights - 6.Ndb5 d5 7.Bf4 Endgame"]
[Black "Three Knights - Nf3 Panov Transposition #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable, but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail } 6... d5 7. cxd5
Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5 { This is a funny retreat, but it is the most ambitious move. } 10.
Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O
{ White has a development lead but Black has the bishop pair. Both sides have slight pawn weaknesses - on d4 and c6. I have played this for both colors. It's quite tricky! }
12... Qd5
{ Black centralizes the queen and increases his influence on the light squares. White has many different ways to play. He can exchange queens himself, move his queen, or leave his queen and allow Black to make the exchange, although the second player is hardly obligated to do so.   In general, we do not have to memorize too much here. It is more important to learn different plans and get a feel for the position. Black has to be a bit careful with his king, which will often take shelter on f7. White has to try to maintain some control of the position, as Black not only has the Bishop-pair but pawn play - with ...c5 as well as a potential advance of the kingside pawns. }
13. Bf4
{ The bishop looks active here, but it is also a bit exposed. The d4-pawn lacks support - it would be hanging if White moves his knight - but usually Black should not bother with the pawn. }
13... f6
{ This move looks very surprising at first. Black makes another pawn move while he only has his queen out and White has already castled.   The little pawn move covers the e5- and g5-squares so White’s f3-knight if rather ineffective. Often Black will just put his king on f7 where it is actually quite safe while also covering the pawns on the third rank. }
14. Rfc1 g5
{ This aggressive thrust is a common reaction to  Bf4  ideas, and is explored deeper in the main course. Black could also play  14...Be7  . }
