[White "White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3 #1"]
[Black "White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. g3
{ This is a tricky move order if Black is not prepared. The main lines of the Four Knights have held up very well for Black for a long time, so White tries to avoid the main lines. }
5... e5 { A very direct attempt to challenge White's move order. } 6. Nb5
{ Other moves offer no challenge whatsoever but are nevertheless analysed in the main course. }
6... Bb4+ { This is surprisingly disruptive. } 7. N1c3 d6
{ Black is prepared to give up his b4-bishop, as he develops quickly in this line. }
8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Be6
{ Black's 'Sveshnikov' structure may not appeal to some, but Black has such smooth development he is doing well. Even though White has the bishop pair Black should not refrain from opening the position because White is not really ready for it. If White tends to his c4-pawn he can quickly come under pressure. }
