1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. g3 e5
{ A very direct attempt to challenge White's move order. } 6. Nb5
{ Other moves offer no challenge whatsoever but are nevertheless analysed in the main course. }
6... Bb4+ { This is surprisingly disruptive. } 7. Bd2
{ White wants to exhcange the bishops to exploit the weakened d6-square. Black does not have to cooperate. }
7... a6 { This leads to sharp play. } 8. Bxb4
{ This looks the most challenging. } 8... axb5 9. Bd6 Qa5+ 10. Nc3
{ 10.Nd2  is the best try for White and is covered in the full repertoire. }
10... b4 11. Nb5 b3+ 12. Nc3 Ne4 13. Qd3 Nxd6
{ 13...Nxc3  14.bxc3  Nd4  15.Bg2  Nc2+  16.Kd2  Nxa1  17.Rxa1  in S.Ernst - Bruzon Batista, Wijk aan Zee 2012, but the position was not so clear at this point. }
14. Qxd6 Nb4
{ Not only threatening ...Nc2+, but introducing the possibility of ...Ra6, which could be good for offense and defense! }
