1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable, but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qd5
{ Black centralizes the queen and increases his influence on the light squares. White has many different ways to play. He can exchange queens himself, move his queen, or leave his queen and allow Black to make the exchange, although the second player is hardly obligated to do so.   In general, we do not have to memorize too much here. It is more important to learn different plans and get a feel for the position. Black has to be a bit careful with his king, which will often take shelter on f7. White has to try to maintain some control of the position, as Black not only has the Bishop-pair but pawn play - with ...c5 as well as a potential advance of the kingside pawns. }
13. Qxd5
{ This not completely illogical because White has a large lead in development and a queenside pawn majority. However, exchanging in this manner improves Black's pawn structure, and of course the bishop pair is an asset in the endgame. }
13... cxd5 14. Bf4 f6
{ Strangely enough, Black will continue to move his pawns. First he covers the e5-square. }
15. Rfc1 h5
{ Black may still play ...g5 and ...h4 to gain space, so White halts the pawns' advance. }
16. h4 Rh7
{ A rather unconventional development, but it works. The first point is to guard to seventh rank. }
17. Ne1 Rb7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3 #2"]
[Black "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course.   In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. }
7. Nb3 Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. Qe2
{ This is the main line. White protects the e4-pawn, and also covers the c4-pawn to prepare Bg2. }
9... d6
{ Bringing some protection to the dark squares. Black has to time ...Bxc3 carefully, because if the capture is done too early White will be able to play Ba3 and the bishop will slice through Black's position. Now White chooses between immediate aggression in the center or the prevention of doubled pawns. }
10. f4 { This is the older line. } 10... Nc6
{ Simply retreating is best.   10...Bxc3+?  11.bxc3  Nc6  12.Ba3!  is something to avoid. }
11. Be3
{ With this move White prepares castling kingside. Other moves leave the g1-a7 diagonal open, and after so many pawn advances White's king can easily become exposed. }
11... Bxc3+ { Now that there is no Ba3, it's time to smash the pawns. } 12.
bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5
{ Blocking e4-e5 and taking a stand on the dark-squares. If allowed, Black will follow up with ...b6 to prevent c4-c5. Then ...Be6 or ...Ba6 will lay siege to the c4-pawn. }
*

